                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Use Plural Nouns for Collections:</strong> Always use plural nouns for collection resources (e.g., <code>/users</code>, <code>/products</code>).</li>
                    <li><strong>Use Nouns, Not Verbs, in URIs:</strong> URIs should identify resources, not actions (e.g., <code>/users</code> not <code>/getUsers</code>). The HTTP method defines the action.</li>
                    <li><strong>Leverage HTTP Methods Appropriately:</strong>
                        <ul>
                            <li><span class="method-get">GET</span>: Retrieve a resource or a list of resources. (Safe & Idempotent)</li>
                            <li><span class="method-post">POST</span>: Create a new resource. (Not Idempotent)</li>
                            <li><span class="method-put">PUT</span>: Update/replace an existing resource, or create if it doesn't exist (full replacement). (Idempotent)</li>
                            <li><span class="method-patch">PATCH</span>: Partially update an existing resource. (Idempotent)</li>
                            <li><span class="method-delete">DELETE</span>: Remove a resource. (Idempotent)</li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                    <li><strong>Use Clear Status Codes:</strong> Return appropriate HTTP status codes to indicate the outcome of the request (e.g., <code>200 OK</code>, <code>201 Created</code>, <code>204 No Content</code>, <code>400 Bad Request</code>, <code>401 Unauthorized</code>, <code>403 Forbidden</code>, <code>404 Not Found</code>, <code>500 Internal Server Error</code>).</li>
                    <li><strong>Provide Meaningful Error Messages:</strong> When an error occurs, return a JSON object with a clear error code, message, and potentially details for developers.</li>
                    <li><strong>Support Filtering, Sorting, Pagination:</strong> For collection endpoints (e.g., <code>GET /users</code>), allow clients to filter, sort, and paginate results using query parameters (e.g., <code>/users?status=active&sort=name,asc&page=2&limit=10</code>).</li>
                    <li><strong>Versioning:</strong> Use versioning (e.g., <code>/v1/users</code>) to manage changes to your API without breaking existing clients.</li>
                    <li><strong>Use HATEOAS (Optional but Recommended):</strong> Include links to related resources in your API responses to guide clients on possible next actions.</li>
                    <li><strong>Secure Your API:</strong> Implement authentication (e.g., OAuth2, JWT) and authorization. Use HTTPS.</li>
                    <li><strong>Document Your API:</strong> Tools like OpenAPI (Swagger) can help generate and maintain interactive documentation.</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
