                                    <p><span class="status-code">204 No Content</span></p>
                                </td>
                                <td>
                                    <p><span class="status-code">500 Internal Server Error</span></p>
                                </td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="section">
            <div class="section-header" onclick="toggleSection(this)">
                General API Guidelines
                <span class="toggle-icon">&rsaquo;</span>
            </div>
            <div class="section-content">
                <h3>1. Use Nouns for URIs, Verbs for HTTP Methods</h3>
                <p>URIs should identify resources (e.g., <code>/users</code>, <code>/users/{id}</code>), not actions. HTTP methods (GET, POST, PUT, PATCH, DELETE) define the action to be performed on that resource.</p>

                <h3>2. Consistent Plural Nouns for Collections</h3>
                <p>Always use plural nouns for collection resources (e.g., <code>/users</code>, <code>/products</code>). Singular nouns for specific resources (e.g., <code>/users/123</code>).</p>

                <h3>3. Use Appropriate HTTP Status Codes</h3>
                <p>Communicate the outcome of an API request clearly using standard HTTP status codes (e.g., <span class="highlight-green">200 OK</span>, <span class="highlight-green">201 Created</span>, <span class="highlight-green">204 No Content</span> for success; <span class="highlight-red">400 Bad Request</span>, <span class="highlight-red">401 Unauthorized</span>, <span class="highlight-red">403 Forbidden</span>, <span class="highlight-red">404 Not Found</span> for client errors; <span class="highlight-red">500 Internal Server Error</span> for server errors).</p>

                <h3>4. Use Request Body for Data (POST, PUT, PATCH)</h3>
                <p>When creating or updating resources, send the data in the request body, typically as JSON, rather than in query parameters (especially for <code>POST</code> and <code>PUT</code>).</p>

                <h3>5. Idempotency</h3>
                <p>A request is idempotent if it can be called multiple times without changing the result beyond the initial call.
                    <ul>
                        <li><span class="http-method method-get">GET</span>, <span class="http-method method-put">PUT</span>, <span class="http-method method-delete">DELETE</span> are generally idempotent.</li>
                        <li><span class="http-method method-post">POST</span> is generally NOT idempotent (repeated calls create new resources).</li>
                        <li><span class="http-method method-patch">PATCH</span> is generally NOT idempotent unless the patch document itself is idempotent (e.g., "set status to 'active'" vs. "increment count by 1").</li>
                    </ul>
                </p>

                <h3>6. Versioning</h3>
                <p>Consider API versioning (e.g., <code>/v1/users</code>) to manage changes without breaking existing client integrations.</p>

                <h3>7. Error Handling</h3>
                <p>Provide consistent and informative error responses, typically in JSON format, detailing the error and how to fix it.</p>

            </div>
        </div>

    </div>

