            Introduction to REST Principles
            <span class="toggle-icon">▶</span>
        </div>
        <div class="content">
            <p>REST (Representational State Transfer) is an architectural style for networked hypermedia applications. When applied to web services, it emphasizes:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Resources:</strong> Everything is a resource (e.g., a user, a list of users). Resources are identified by URLs.</li>
                <li><strong>HTTP Methods:</strong> Standard HTTP methods (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE, PATCH) are used to perform operations on resources.</li>
                <li><strong>Statelessness:</strong> Each request from a client to a server must contain all the information needed to understand the request.</li>
                <li><strong>Uniform Interface:</strong> A consistent way of interacting with resources.</li>
                <li><strong>HATEOAS (Hypermedia As The Engine Of Application State):</strong> (Advanced) Resources include links to related resources.</li>
            </ul>
            <p>Following these principles leads to more scalable, maintainable, and understandable APIs.</p>
        </div>
