            <ul class="problem-list">
                <li><strong>Verb in URI:</strong> "getUsers" contains a verb ("get"), which violates the principle of URIs identifying resources (nouns).</li>
                <li><strong>Redundant Method:</strong> The method "GET" already implies retrieval, making "get" in the URI redundant.</li>
                <li><strong>Lack of Specificity:</strong> If the intention is to retrieve *all* users, the plural noun is usually sufficient. If it's for a specific user, an ID should be part of the path.</li>
            </ul>
            <h3>Corrected Endpoint</h3>
            <div class="corrected-endpoint"><span class="method GET">GET</span> <code>/users</code></div>
            <div class="status-codes">
                <strong>Status Codes:</strong>
                <ul>
                    <li><code>200 OK</code>: Successfully retrieved the list of users.</li>
                    <li><code>204 No Content</code>: If the list is empty (some APIs might return 200 with an empty array/list).</li>
                    <li><code>401 Unauthorized</code>: If authentication is required but missing/invalid.</li>
                    <li><code>403 Forbidden</code>: If the authenticated user doesn't have permission to view users.</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            <p><strong>Explanation:</strong> The URI <code>/users</code> clearly identifies the "users" collection resource. The GET method indicates that we are retrieving the representation of this resource (i.e., a list of all users).</p>
            <hr/>
            <p><strong>For retrieving a single user:</strong></p>
            <div class="corrected-endpoint"><span class="method GET">GET</span> <code>/users/{id}</code></div>
            <div class="status-codes">
                <strong>Status Codes:</strong>
                <ul>
                    <li><code>200 OK</code>: Successfully retrieved the user.</li>
                    <li><code>404 Not Found</code>: If a user with the specified ID does not exist.</li>
                    <li><code>401 Unauthorized</code>: If authentication is required but missing/invalid.</li>
                    <li><code>403 Forbidden</code>: If the authenticated user doesn't have permission to view this specific user.</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            <p><strong>Explanation:</strong> <code>/users/{id}</code> identifies a specific user resource within the <code>users</code> collection.</p>
