                <ul>
                    <li><code>201 Created</code>: Successfully created the user. The response body should contain the newly created user resource, and the <code>Location</code> header should point to its URI (e.g., <code>/users/123</code>).</li>
                    <li><code>400 Bad Request</code>: If the request body is missing required fields or data is invalid (e.g., name is too short).</li>
                    <li><code>401 Unauthorized</code>: If authentication is required but missing/invalid.</li>
                    <li><code>403 Forbidden</code>: If the authenticated user doesn't have permission to create users.</li>
                    <li><code>409 Conflict</code>: If a user with the same unique identifier (e.g., email) already exists.</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            <p><strong>Explanation:</strong> The POST method on the <code>/users</code> collection resource indicates that a new resource should be added to that collection. The user data (e.g., <code>{"name": "Jo", "email": "jo@example.com"}</code>) would be sent in the request body as JSON.</p>
