                <li><strong>Ambiguous Scope:</strong> "AllUsers" is vague. Is it truly *all* users in the system, or a specific subset?</li>
                <li><strong>PUT Semantics:</strong> PUT is typically used to *replace* an entire resource at a known URI. If this endpoint is meant to modify *parts* of multiple users or perform a complex bulk operation, PUT might not be the most appropriate. If it's replacing the *entire collection* of users with a new one, then PUT on <code>/users</code> could be valid, but this is rare.</li>
                <li><strong>Lack of Idempotence (Potentially):</strong> If "updateAllUsers" implies applying a change to existing users without fully replacing the entire collection, then repeated calls might have different effects, violating PUT's idempotence principle.</li>
            </ul>
            <h3>Corrected Endpoints (Multiple Scenarios)</h3>

            <h4>Scenario 1: Replacing the entire collection of users (less common but valid for PUT)</h4>
            <div class="corrected-endpoint"><span class="method PUT">PUT</span> <code>/users</code></div>
            <div class="status-codes">
                <strong>Status Codes:</strong>
                <ul>
                    <li><code>200 OK</code>: Successfully replaced the entire collection.</li>
                    <li><code>204 No Content</code>: If the replacement was successful and no content is returned.</li>
                    <li><code>400 Bad Request</code>: If the request body (the new collection) is invalid.</li>
                    <li><code>401 Unauthorized</code>, <code>403 Forbidden</code>.</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            <p><strong>Explanation:</strong> This assumes you are sending a complete, new list of users in the request body, which will *replace* the existing <code>/users</code> collection. This is a very powerful and potentially destructive operation, usually not what "updateAllUsers" implies.</p>

            <h4>Scenario 2: Partially updating multiple users (Batch Update)</h4>
            <div class="corrected-endpoint"><span class="method PATCH">PATCH</span> <code>/users</code></div>
            <div class="status-codes">
                <strong>Status Codes:</strong>
                <ul>
                    <li><code>200 OK</code>: Successfully applied partial updates to users. Response might contain details of updated users or success/failure for each.</li>
                    <li><code>207 Multi-Status</code>: (WebDAV extension, sometimes used) If individual updates within the batch can have different outcomes.</li>
                    <li><code>400 Bad Request</code>: If the batch request format is invalid.</li>
                    <li><code>401 Unauthorized</code>, <code>403 Forbidden</code>.</li>
                    <li><code>404 Not Found</code>: If some users in the batch do not exist.</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            <p><strong>Explanation:</strong> A <code>PATCH</code> request to the <code>/users</code> collection implies applying a set of partial modifications to multiple resources within that collection. The request body would contain instructions on which users to update and what changes to apply (e.g., an array of objects, each specifying a user ID and the fields to change).</p>

            <h4>Scenario 3: Updating a single user (most common "update" scenario)</h4>
            <div class="corrected-endpoint"><span class="method PUT">PUT</span> <code>/users/{id}</code></div>
            <p><strong>Explanation:</strong> To *replace* an existing user resource entirely with new data. The request body would contain the complete, updated representation of that user.</p>
            <div class="corrected-endpoint"><span class="method PATCH">PATCH</span> <code>/users/{id}</code></div>
            <div class="status-codes">
                <strong>Status Codes:</strong>
                <ul>
                    <li><code>200 OK</code>: Successfully updated the user.</li>
                    <li><code>400 Bad Request</code>: If the request body is invalid.</li>
                    <li><code>404 Not Found</code>: If the user with the specified ID does not exist.</li>
                    <li><code>401 Unauthorized</code>, <code>403 Forbidden</code>.</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            <p><strong>Explanation:</strong> To *partially modify* an existing user resource. The request body would contain only the fields to be changed.</p>
        </div>
